@node greader-read
@subsection @code{greader-read}
The @code{greader-read} command is the core function for starting
text-to-speech synthesis in Greader. It can be invoked with
@code{C-r <spc>}.

@itemize
@item
@strong{Basic Functionality:} When called, @code{greader-read} starts
reading the buffer content from the current cursor position, advancing
sentence by sentence.
@item
@strong{Prefix Argument (@code{C-u C-r <spc>}):} Jumps to the last
reading position and starts reading from there. This can be disabled by
setting @code{greader-use-prefix} to @code{nil}.
@item
@strong{Reading a Region:} If a region is selected, Greader will only
read the selected text. Note that this uses buffer narrowing, so
navigation is limited to the selected region. For an alternative, see
@code{greader-queue-mode}.
@item
@strong{Other Features:} @code{greader-read} also integrates with
``tired mode'' for automatic adjustments and a timer for reading for a
set duration.
@end itemize

@node Minor Modes
@section Minor Modes
Greader provides several minor modes to extend its functionality:

@menu
* Timer and Tired Modes::
* greader-queue-mode::
* greader-compile-mode::
* greader-translate-mode::
@end menu

@itemize
@item
@strong{@code{greader-continuous-mode}:} Automatically turn pages in
modes like @code{info-mode}.

@itemize
@item
This minor mode allows Greader to automatically turn pages in multi-page
modes. When active, instead of stopping at the end of the buffer,
Greader will call the appropriate function to display the next page and
continue reading.

@item
Greader tries to automatically guess the function to call to turn the
page. It does this by checking the command bound to the @code{SPC} key.
This works in many modes, like @code{info-mode}.

@item
You can customize this behavior for other modes by using the
@code{greader-continuous-modes} variable. This variable is an alist that
maps major modes to the function that should be called to turn the page.

@item
For example, to make @code{greader-continuous-mode} work with
@code{nov-mode}, you would add the following to your configuration:

@verbatim
(add-to-list 'greader-continuous-modes '(nov-mode . nov-next-document))
@end verbatim

@item
You can also exclude certain major modes from this behavior using the
@code{greader-continuous-excluded-modes} variable.

@item
If the page-turning function in a mode is not bound to @code{SPC}, you
can specify a different key with the @code{greader-continuous-key}
variable.

@end itemize

@item
@strong{@code{greader-translate-mode}:} On-the-fly translation of the
buffer.

@item
@strong{@code{greader-enriched-mode}:} Announce links and other
clickable elements.

@item
@strong{@code{greader-dict-mode}:} Use custom dictionaries for
pronunciation. @code{greader-dict-mode} allows you to create custom
pronunciation rules for words or patterns. This is useful for correcting
mispronunciations by the text-to-speech engine.

@end itemize

@subsection How it Works
You can define two types of dictionary entries:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Word:} A whole-word substitution. For example, if you define a
``word'' entry for ``Emacs'', it will only replace ``Emacs'' when it
appears as a standalone word, not in ``EmacsLisp''.
@item
@strong{Match:} A literal substring substitution. For example, a
``match'' entry for ``read'' could apply to ``reading'' and ``reader''.
Matches can also be regular expressions for more complex patterns.
@end itemize

@subsection Dictionary Visibility
Greader supports three levels of dictionary visibility:

@itemize
@item
@strong{@code{global}:} The default dictionary, applied everywhere.
@item
@strong{@code{mode}:} A dictionary specific to a major mode (e.g., a
dictionary for @code{org-mode} buffers).
@item
@strong{@code{buffer}:} A dictionary that applies only to the current
buffer.
@end itemize

You can change the visibility for the current buffer using the
@code{greader-dict-change-dictionary} command (@code{C-r d c}).

To set a default visibility for a specific mode, you can add a hook to
your Emacs configuration. For example, to use @code{mode} visibility for
@code{info-mode}:

@verbatim
(add-hook 'info-mode-hook
          (lambda ()
            (greader-dict-mode 1)
            (greader-dict--set-file 'mode)))
@end verbatim

@subsection Usage
@strong{Enable the mode:} @code{M-x greader-dict-mode}

