@node Timer and Tired Modes
@subsection Timer and Tired Modes

Greader provides three cooperating minor modes for time-limited and
sleep-friendly reading: @code{greader-timer-mode},
@code{greader-tired-mode}, and @code{greader-auto-tired-mode}.

@subsubsection @code{greader-timer-mode}

@code{greader-timer-mode} (@kbd{C-r t}) stops reading automatically
after a configurable number of minutes.  When enabled, a countdown
timer is armed each time @code{greader-read} starts.  On expiry,
reading stops.

By default (@code{greader-soft-timer} is @code{t}) the current sentence
is finished before stopping.  Set @code{greader-soft-timer} to
@code{nil} for an immediate hard cutoff.

Relevant variables:
@itemize
@item
@code{greader-timer} --- duration in minutes (default 10).
@item
@code{greader-soft-timer} --- if @code{t} (default), finish the current
sentence before stopping; if @code{nil}, stop immediately.
@end itemize

@subsubsection @code{greader-tired-mode}

@code{greader-tired-mode} (@kbd{C-r s}) is designed for listening in
bed: enabling it implicitly enables @code{greader-timer-mode}.

When the reading timer expires, greader arms a second, idle-based
timer.  Two things can then happen:

@enumerate
@item
@strong{You press any key} (you are still awake): the idle timer is
cancelled and reading resumes automatically from where it stopped.
The key press is consumed --- it does not execute its normal command.
@item
@strong{You do nothing for @code{greader-tired-time} seconds} (you fell
asleep): the point is moved back to where you originally called
@code{greader-read}, so next time you open the buffer you find the text
you actually heard.
@end enumerate

When @code{greader-soft-timer} is enabled (the default), the idle timer
is armed only after the last sentence has finished being read, not at
the moment the reading timer expires.  This ensures that pressing a key
while the final sentence is still playing does not trigger an unwanted
restart.

Calling @code{greader-stop} explicitly while the last sentence is
playing (soft-timer case) cancels the tired-mode wait entirely ---
point is not moved back.

Disabling @code{greader-tired-mode} also disables
@code{greader-timer-mode}, unless you had enabled the timer
independently beforehand.

Relevant variables:
@itemize
@item
@code{greader-tired-time} --- idle seconds to wait before moving point
back (default 60).
@end itemize

@subsubsection @code{greader-auto-tired-mode}

@code{greader-auto-tired-mode} automatically activates
@code{greader-tired-mode} within a configurable nightly time window and
deactivates it in the morning.  Enable it once with @kbd{M-x
greader-auto-tired-mode}; it then manages tired mode on its own every
day.

Intervals that cross midnight (e.g., 22:00--07:00) are handled
correctly.

Relevant variables:
@itemize
@item
@code{greader-auto-tired-mode-time} --- hour to activate tired mode, as
a string (default @code{"22"}).
@item
@code{greader-auto-tired-time-end} --- hour to deactivate tired mode, as
a string (default @code{"07"}).
@end itemize

@node greader-queue-mode
@subsection @code{greader-queue-mode}
@code{greader-queue-mode} lets you assemble a playlist of text regions
within the current buffer and read them in sequence. Useful when you
want to read only selected parts of a document, or when the region is
non-contiguous. When @code{greader-queue-mode} is active,
@code{greader-mode} is temporarily suspended; it is re-enabled
automatically when you disable @code{greader-queue-mode}.

@strong{Enable:} @code{M-x greader-queue-mode}

@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33 
@headitem 
Keybinding
 @tab Command
 @tab Description
@item 
@code{C-r RET}
 @tab @code{greader-queue-add-element}
 @tab Add the selected region (or current position) to the queue.
@item 
@code{C-r SPC}
 @tab @code{greader-queue-read}
 @tab Start reading the queue.
@item 
@code{C-r <left>}
 @tab @code{greader-queue-backward}
 @tab Move to the previous element in the queue.
@item 
@code{C-r <right>}
 @tab @code{greader-queue-forward}
 @tab Move to the next element in the queue.
@item 
@code{C-r .}
 @tab @code{greader-queue-stop}
 @tab Stop reading.
@end multitable

Additional commands available via @code{M-x}:
@code{greader-queue-remove-element}, @code{greader-queue-reset-queue}.

@node greader-compile-mode
@subsection @code{greader-compile-mode}
@code{greader-compile-mode} is for users who want to edit and recompile
eSpeak-NG voice dictionaries from within Emacs. It is not needed for
ordinary text-to-speech use.

@strong{Prerequisites:} Set @code{greader-compile-dictsource} to the
list of directories containing your eSpeak-NG dictionary source files
before enabling this mode:

@lisp
(setq greader-compile-dictsource
      '("/path/to/espeak-ng-data/dictsource/"))
@end lisp

Paths must end with a slash. The variable is a list, so you can specify
multiple directories.

@strong{File naming convention:} eSpeak-NG dictionary source files must
follow the pattern @code{XX_suffix}, where @code{XX} is a two-letter
language code (e.g., @code{en_extra}, @code{it_rules}).
@code{greader-compile-mode} uses the filename to infer the language to
compile.

@strong{Enable:} @code{M-x greader-compile-mode}

@strong{Auto-compilation on save:} Once enabled, saving any dictionary
source file whose directory is in @code{greader-compile-dictsource}
automatically runs @code{espeak --compile=XX} for the corresponding
language. If the eSpeak-NG data directory is not writable by your user,
you will be prompted for your administrator password.

@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33
@headitem
Keybinding
 @tab Command
 @tab Description
@item
@code{C-r c}
 @tab @code{greader-compile-at-point}
 @tab Add the word at point to the dictionary and recompile. With a
prefix argument, prompts for the word.
@end multitable

@code{greader-compile} --- Compile eSpeak-NG definitions interactively.
With a prefix argument, prompts for the language code; without, infers
it from the current file name.

@code{greader-compile-goto-source} --- Visit the dictionary source file
currently used by @code{greader-compile-at-point}.

@node greader-translate-mode
@subsection @code{greader-translate-mode}
@code{greader-translate-mode} is a minor mode that allows for on-the-fly
translation of the buffer being read. When this mode is active, each
sentence is translated before being sent to the text-to-speech engine.

@menu
* Usage: Usage 2.
* Configuration::
* Prerequisites and Implications::
@end menu

@node Usage 2
@subsubsection Usage
@enumerate 
@item
Enable the minor mode with @code{M-x greader-translate-mode}.
@item
Start reading with @code{greader-read} (@code{C-r <spc>}). The text will
be translated and read in the destination language.
@end enumerate

@node Configuration
@subsubsection Configuration
For the translation to work, you need to configure a few variables:

@itemize
@item
@strong{@code{greader-translate-lang-src}}: Sets the source language of
the text. This value must be a valid language code (e.g., @code{"en"}
for English, @code{"fr"} for French).

@verbatim
(setq greader-translate-lang-src "en")
@end verbatim

@item
@strong{Destination Language}: The language to translate to is set via
the @code{greader-set-language} command (@code{C-r l}), which in turn
sets the language for the speech synthesis backend.

@item
@strong{@code{greader-translate-function}}: Allows you to specify the
function to use for translation. The default setting is
@code{greader-translate-with-google}, which relies on the
@code{google-translate} package.

@item
@strong{@code{greader-translate-timeout}}: Specifies the maximum time in
seconds to wait for a response from the translation service before
generating an error. The default value is 30 seconds.

@end itemize

@node Prerequisites and Implications
@subsubsection Prerequisites and Implications
@itemize
@item
@strong{Dependencies}: This feature requires the installation of the
@code{google-translate} package and its dependencies.
@item
@strong{Internet Connection}: An internet connection is required to
contact the translation services.
@item
@strong{Privacy}: Using @code{greader-translate-with-google} involves
sending the buffer's text to external services (like Google Translate).
This may have privacy implications. Users are subject to the terms of
service and privacy policies of the translation service provider. It is
recommended to be aware of what data is being sent.
@end itemize

@node Backends
@section Backends
Switch backends with @code{C-r b} (@code{greader-change-backend}) or by
setting @code{greader-current-backend} in your configuration.

@menu
* eSpeak / eSpeak NG::
* Speech Dispatcher::
* Piper::
* macOS say::
