@node Audiobook Creation
@section Audiobook Creation
The @code{greader-audiobook-buffer} command converts the current buffer
into a collection of WAV audio files, optionally transcoding them to
MP3/M4A/FLAC and bundling them into a ZIP or M4B audiobook container.

@menu
* Backend support::
* Piper and audiobook generation::
* Error handling::
* Audiobook customization::
@end menu

@node Backend support
@subsection Backend support
Audiobook generation uses the @strong{current greader TTS backend}
(@code{greader-current-backend}), so the same voice, language, and rate
you use for live reading are applied to the audiobook. Supported
backends:

@multitable @columnfractions 0.50 0.50 
@headitem 
Backend
 @tab Notes
@item 
eSpeak / eSpeak NG
 @tab @strong{Recommended.} Fast, stable, and reliable on any text.
@item 
Piper
 @tab High-quality neural TTS. Requires @code{piper.sh} v2 (see below).
May be unstable on long or complex texts.
@item 
macOS @code{say}
 @tab Native macOS speech; outputs 16-bit PCM WAV. @strong{See stability
note below.}
@item 
Speech Dispatcher
 @tab @strong{Not supported} --- @code{spd-say} cannot write WAV files.
@end multitable

@strong{eSpeak is the only backend with consistently optimal performance
for audiobook generation.} AI-based backends (Piper, macOS @code{say}
with neural voices such as Siri) are designed for short, interactive
utterances and can become unreliable when converting long, complex texts
such as books:

@itemize
@item
They may produce truncated or garbled audio blocks while reporting
success (exit code 0). The @code{greader-audiobook-min-wav-size} check
catches the worst cases, but subtle corruption may go undetected.
@item
On very long sentences or paragraphs they may @strong{hang
indefinitely}. Because block conversion is synchronous, a hung backend
freezes Emacs entirely; @code{greader-audiobook-on-error} cannot
intervene. Use @code{C-g} to interrupt and kill the process manually.
@end itemize

If you want to use a neural voice for an audiobook, consider splitting
the source buffer into smaller chunks before converting.

@node Piper and audiobook generation
@subsection Piper and audiobook generation
The @code{piper.sh} wrapper script shipped with greader supports an
optional second argument: the output WAV file path. When present, piper
writes to that file instead of playing audio in real time. No additional
Emacs configuration is required; the model path is read from
@code{piper.sh} as usual.

If you maintain a custom copy of @code{piper.sh} in your @code{PATH},
update it to the current version from the greader repository to enable
audiobook support.

@node Error handling
@subsection Error handling
AI-based backends can produce silent failures (corrupted or near-empty
audio) alongside outright crashes. Greader detects both:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Non-zero exit code} --- the backend process failed; the error
buffer (@code{*espeak-output*}, @code{*piper-output*},
@code{*say-output*}, @dots{}) will contain details.
@item
@strong{WAV too small} --- the output file is below
@code{greader-audiobook-min-wav-size} bytes even if the backend reported
success; the block is treated as corrupt.
@end itemize

The variable @code{greader-audiobook-on-error} controls what happens
when a block fails:

@multitable {@code{skip}} {Signal an error and abort conversion immediately (default).} 
@headitem 
Value
 @tab Behaviour
@item 
@code{stop}
 @tab Signal an error and abort conversion immediately (default).
@item 
@code{skip}
 @tab Log the block number and continue with the next block.
@item 
@code{ask}
 @tab Ask interactively whether to skip or abort.
@end multitable

When blocks are skipped a summary message lists their numbers at the end
of conversion.

@node Audiobook customization
@subsection Audiobook customization
Use @code{M-x customize-group RET greader-audiobook RET} for the full
list of options. Key variables:

@multitable @columnfractions 0.33 0.33 0.33 
@headitem 
Variable
 @tab Default
 @tab Description
@item 
@code{greader-audiobook-base-directory}
 @tab @code{~/.emacs.d/audiobooks/}
 @tab Root directory for generated audiobooks.
@item 
@code{greader-audiobook-block-size}
 @tab @code{"15"}
 @tab Block size: a string means minutes, a number means characters.
@item 
@code{greader-audiobook-transcode-wave-files}
 @tab @code{nil}
 @tab Transcode WAV blocks via ffmpeg.
@item 
@code{greader-audiobook-transcode-format}
 @tab @code{"mp3"}
 @tab Target format for transcoding.
@item 
@code{greader-audiobook-on-error}
 @tab @code{stop}
 @tab Error policy: @code{stop}, @code{skip}, or @code{ask}.
@item 
@code{greader-audiobook-min-wav-size}
 @tab @code{1000}
 @tab Minimum WAV size in bytes; smaller files are treated as corrupt.
@item 
@code{greader-audiobook-create-m4b}
 @tab @code{nil}
 @tab Bundle all blocks into a single M4B audiobook file.
@item 
@code{greader-audiobook-compress}
 @tab @code{t}
 @tab Compress the audiobook directory into a ZIP file.
@end multitable

@node Customization
@section Customization
You can customize Greader by setting variables in your Emacs
configuration file. Use @code{M-x customize-group RET greader RET} to
see the available options.

Some of the customizable variables are:

@itemize
@item
@code{greader-backends}: A list of available TTS backends.
@item
@code{greader-current-backend}: The default TTS backend to use.
@item
@code{greader-timer}: Reading timer duration in minutes (default 10).
Used by @code{greader-timer-mode}.
@item
@code{greader-soft-timer}: If @code{t} (the default), finishes the
current sentence before stopping at timer expiration.  Set to @code{nil}
for an immediate hard cutoff.
@item
@code{greader-tired-time}: Idle seconds to wait after the reading timer
expires before moving point back (default 60).  Used by
@code{greader-tired-mode}.
@item
@code{greader-auto-tired-mode-time}: Hour (as a string, e.g.@:
@code{"22"}) at which @code{greader-auto-tired-mode} activates tired
mode.
@item
@code{greader-auto-tired-time-end}: Hour (as a string, e.g.@:
@code{"07"}) at which @code{greader-auto-tired-mode} deactivates tired
mode.  Intervals crossing midnight are supported.
@item
@code{greader-backward-acoustic-feedback}: If @code{t}, plays a brief
beep when the cursor returns to the previous reading position after
backward navigation. Default @code{nil}.
@item
@code{greader-backward-seconds}: Number of seconds to wait at the
previous sentence before automatically returning to the reading
position. Default @code{5}.
@item
@code{greader-dict-save-after-time}: Idle time in seconds before the
dictionary is saved automatically. Default @code{30}. (Requires
@code{greader-dict-mode}.)
@end itemize

